<span id="freeTextContainer11555343100446901772">Vincent Van Gogh. With great skill and graceful simplicity, Irving Stone has illustrated the life and beauty of an individual whose joy, whose fervent necessity of painting enraptured the young man as his paintings&apos; vitality has burst through the entirety of the art world--but died before he could ever know. &quot;Not an hour passes but that I look at his paintings and find there a new faith, a new meaning of life&quot;--Van Gogh: the artist that has caught my eye and the essence and intensity of life wit</span>
  <span id="freeText11555343100446901772" style="display:none">Vincent Van Gogh. With great skill and graceful simplicity, Irving Stone has illustrated the life and beauty of an individual whose joy, whose fervent necessity of painting enraptured the young man as his paintings' vitality has burst through the entirety of the art world--but died before he could ever know. "Not an hour passes but that I look at his paintings and find there a new faith, a new meaning of life"--Van Gogh: the artist that has caught my eye and the essence and intensity of life with an impression of emotion like no other, the <i>world's</i> most mad, pained, yet beautiful individual... will not be forgotten.</span>
